Sentencas: The possibility to control oxygen transport in one of the most promising solid oxide fuel cell cathode materials, La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-delta, by controlling lattice strain raises questions regarding the contribution of atomic scale effects.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: Here, high-resolution transmission electron microscopy revealed the different atomic structures in La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-delta thin films grown under tensile and compressive strain conditions.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: The atomic structure of the tensile-strained film indicated significant local concentration of the oxygen vacancies, with the average value of the oxygen non-stoichiometry being much larger than for the compressive-strained film.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: In addition to the vacancy concentration differences that are measured by isotope exchange depth profiling, significant vacancy ordering was found in tensile-strained films.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: This understanding might be useful for tuning the atomic structure of La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-delta thin films to optimize cathode performance.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: Strain engineering can enhance oxygen transport in cathodes in solid oxide fuel cells.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films

Sentencas: Here, atomic scale imaging is used to probe local structures in tensile- and compressive-strained La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-delta films, revealing higher oxygen vacancy concentration in tensile films, and vacancy ordering.
Titulo: Strain-induced structure and oxygen transport interactions in epitaxial La0.6Sr0.4CoO3-δ thin films
